[2] South Australia: human
Date: Thu 17 Mar 2022
Source: ABC News [edited]
https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-03-18/sa-records-first-confirmed-japanese-encephalitis-virus-death/100920626


Key points
----------
- There have been 8 confirmed Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV) cases in South Australia
- 5 remain in hospital, and another 2 encephalitis cases are under investigation
- Health authorities have now confirmed a suspected fatal case

South Australian (SA) health authorities have confirmed 4 further cases of the mosquito-borne disease Japanese encephalitis, including the state's 1st death. The death was of a person who authorities had earlier suspected may have died with the disease. SA Health said there were now 8 total Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV) cases in the state. Of these, remain in hospital, while 2 have been discharged, SA Health wellbeing director Chris Lease said.

"We can confirm that one of the additional cases includes the person who we previously reported had sadly passed away earlier this month [March 2022]," Dr Lease said. Another 2 cases of encephalitis remain under investigation as potential JEV cases. "It is crucial that we all continue to take extra precautions against mosquitoes and continue to 'fight the bite,'" Dr Lease said.

Most people infected with so-called "flaviviruses" such as JEV, Kokobera virus, West Nile virus and Murray Valley encephalitis do not suffer symptoms or develop a mild fever. But a small proportion will develop encephalitis, which can be fatal or cause long-term neurological damage. Symptoms of encephalitis include confusion, headaches, neck stiffness, tremors, drowsiness and seizures.

Young children have a higher risk of developing encephalitis if infected with JEV. A 4-month-old baby was last week confirmed to have contracted the virus in Victoria.

JEV has also been detected at more than 2 dozen piggeries across 4 states: Queensland, NSW, Victoria and South Australia.

Dr Lease has urged members of the public to try to stop mosquitoes coming indoors and take precautions including insect repellent.

Earlier this week, authorities urged vigilance if people are using mosquito coils, after 2 house fires in Adelaide were linked to the devices this week. "Do not leave them burning unattended and always remember to extinguish them carefully by breaking the smouldering end off, immersing it in water and storing it away from the house to completely cool," Dr Lease said.

--
