[3] Queensland: pig
Date: Wed 16 Mar 2022 21:47 AEST
Source: ABC News [edited]
https://www.abc.net.au/news/2022-03-17/qld-mosquito-virus-japanese-encephalitis-piggery/100913726


Key points
----------
- An expert said the virus had probably been circulating for months before it was recently detected in Australian piggeries
- Biosecurity Queensland organised testing last month [February 2022] when a veterinarian reported increased "reproductive problems" at a piggery in the state's south
- Associate Professor Devine predicted a spike in mosquito-borne disease in Australia as weather patterns changed

The mosquito-borne Japanese encephalitis virus has been discovered at a 2nd Queensland piggery, with an expert warning the potentially deadly disease is most likely "here to stay".

The virus was diagnosed in 18 Australians this month [March 2022] and has been found in 28 piggeries across 4 states -- Queensland, NSW, Victoria and South Australia -- the 1st time an outbreak has occurred outside Australia's far north. Of the people infected, 2 have died.

There are 2 Queensland piggeries that have been affected, including one in the Goondiwindi region. No details have been revealed about the location of the 2nd.

A woman in her 60s with the virus remains in a critical but stable condition in The Prince Charles Hospital, in Brisbane's north. She is the 1st locally acquired Queensland case since 1998.

QIMR [Queensland Institute of Medical Research] Berghofer Medical Research Institute senior mosquito scientist Greg Devine has called for the establishment of a national surveillance system to improve the detection and management of mosquito-borne diseases, including Japanese encephalitis, in the wake of the outbreak. Associate Professor Devine said the virus had probably been circulating for months before it was recently detected in Australian piggeries.

"I think what this Japanese encephalitis outbreak has told us is that our surveillance systems are inadequate," he said. "The fact that it seemed to turn up all at once across many states in dozens of piggeries, and then to have an unprecedented number of human cases emerge as well, suggests that it has been around for quite a while and that we've just missed it. We've been rather overwhelmed by other things like COVID-19 over the last couple of years. But it does mean that people have disinvested in the other surveillance programs. People haven't been paying as much attention. It wasn't on anybody's radar."

Biosecurity Queensland organised testing last month [February] when a veterinarian reported increased "reproductive problems" at a piggery in the state's south. Stillborn piglets can be a sign of Japanese encephalitis. Piglets infected after birth can develop neurological signs in the first 6 months of life. Symptoms can include hind-limb paralysis. Adult sows do not typically show signs of disease.

The virus is transmitted to pigs, horses and humans through mosquito bites. It cannot pass from human to human or from horses. Pigs and wild birds are known as "amplifying hosts," playing a role in spreading the disease via mosquitoes. Commercially produced pork and other pig products are safe to consume.

Japanese encephalitis is generally harmless in humans, but in less than 1% of cases, people can develop encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain, which is fatal in about 30% of patients.

Associate Professor Devine speculated the outbreak was triggered by the warm, wet La Ni√±a weather pattern encouraging infected water birds into areas they rarely venture into and coinciding with vast numbers of mosquitoes.

The most likely vector in Australia is a mosquito dubbed _Cutux annulirostris_, a "large, brown mosquito that loves freshwater. Sometimes they will be in proximity to a piggery," he said. "Pigs can carry very high burdens of the virus and can easily infect mosquitoes. That allows spillover into humans."

Associate Professor Devine predicted a spike in mosquito-borne disease in Australia as weather patterns changed. "There's no doubt that our temperatures are going to increase, and our weather patterns are going to become more unpredictable," he said. "Our future is a warmer one, full of flooding events where the water hangs around for quite a long time, and there's no doubt that the risk of these kinds of diseases, like Japanese encephalitis...increases dramatically."

The head of QIMR Berghofer's mosquito control laboratory called for a nationally coordinated response bringing together health, agriculture and wildlife ecologists to better understand the problem. "We don't have information on migrating bird patterns that we need at the moment," Associate Professor Devine said. "It's possible that feral pigs have got a role in there somewhere too. Back in the 1990s, some surveys did show that feral pigs were certainly more than capable of keeping the virus circulating geographically in an area. We've got millions of feral pigs. But we don't have a great surveillance program for feral pigs in terms of their role in Japanese encephalitis."

Pig producers who notice signs of Japanese encephalitis should immediately contact a veterinarian, Biosecurity Queensland on 13 25 23 or call the Emergency Animal Disease Watch Hotline on 1800 675 888.

[Byline: Janelle Miles]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[It seems odd that in all the reports of JE virus transmission in the 4 states that ProMED has received, there have been no mentions of mosquito surveillance and testing for JE virus until the above report. Historically, Australia has had an active medical entomology community that knows where the vector mosquitoes are breeding as the wet season progresses. In informal communication with previous ProMED moderator and arbovirologist Dr. Charles Calisher, we have wondered if there was any routine vector mosquito trapping and testing underway to identify areas of JE virus transmission before cases in humans and piggeries appear. Dr. Devine's comments above suggest that a vector mosquito surveillance program has not been in place but is needed for JE and other arboviruses. - Mod.TY

